 =20
   =20
      CEO pay
   =20
 =20

If you are the chief executive officer of a public company, you will probab=
ly get most of your pay in stock. If you do the job for a while, you will e=
nd up owning a fair amount of stock. Conceptually, your financial incentive=
s will come in roughly four forms:
=09You own a bunch of stock. If you do a good job, the stock will go up, an=
d you will get richer.=09You have gotten some stock-based awards, like, las=
t year, or two years ago, that haven=E2=80=99t fully vested yet. If you do =
a good job, the stock will go up, and these awards will be worth more. If y=
ou do a terrible job maybe you=E2=80=99ll get fired and the awards won=E2=
=80=99t vest and they=E2=80=99ll be worth zero.=09You will get paid somethi=
ng (cash, stock, whatever)=C2=A0this=C2=A0year. If you do a good job, the b=
oard will pay you more; if you do a bad job they=E2=80=99ll pay you less or=
 fire you.=09You will get paid something=C2=A0next=C2=A0year, and the year=
=C2=A0after; the better job you do now, the more likely you are to keep you=
r job and be well paid in the future.

All of these things can be economically meaningful. For the very richest CE=
Os, No. 1 tends to dominate; Mark Zuckerberg and Warren Buffett get vastly =
richer from a 0.1% increase in their stock prices than from their annual pa=
y packages. (Elon Musk is a mild outlier here.) But traditionally only No. =
3 is =E2=80=9Cexecutive pay.=E2=80=9D
  [3]

That changed last year, though, when the US Securities and Exchange Commiss=
ion adopted new rules requiring companies to report executive =E2=80=9Ccomp=
ensation actually paid=E2=80=9D which means, for our purposes, roughly Nos.=
 2 and 3: =E2=80=9CCompensation actually paid=E2=80=9D includes changes =E2=
=80=9Cin fair value (whether positive or negative) of any awards granted du=
ring the covered fiscal year =E2=80=A6=C2=A0[or] in any prior fiscal year t=
hat are outstanding and unvested as of the end of the covered fiscal year.=
=E2=80=9D So if you get a grant of a million shares in 2021, they vest in 2=
024, and the stock loses $10 per share in 2022, then your =E2=80=9Ccompensa=
tion actually paid=E2=80=9D in 2022 includes negative $10 million of stock =
awards.
Anyway we are now in the first reporting cycle with these rules and the Wal=
l Street Journal rounds up some results:

The stock awards that Elon Musk got for running Tesla lost nearly $10 billi=
on in value last year. Stock declines erased $237 million in compensation f=
or Expedia=E2=80=99s boss and roughly $149 million for Amazon.com Chief Exe=
cutive Andy Jassy.
On the flip side, a pay package initially valued at about $7 million for Re=
generon Pharmaceuticals chief Leonard Schleifer was worth nearly $100 milli=
on at the end of the year. Compensation for T-Mobile CEO Michael Sievert, o=
riginally about $29 million, almost tripled. Occidental Petroleum boss Vick=
i Hollub=E2=80=99s pay quadrupled, from $15 million to about $60 million. .=
..
The numbers show that in 2022 about two-thirds of the top executives at S&P=
 500 companies ended the year with smaller pay packages than they were awar=
ded, at least on paper. Some 140 CEOs earned more money than expected, and =
at 46 companies the CEOs ended with at least double what boards planned to =
pay them for the year, according to a Wall Street Journal analysis of data =
from MyLogIQ.
The latest disclosures, which show the new measure of pay for the three mos=
t recent years, highlight how much CEO pay can fluctuate with market tides =
and other factors=E2=80=94something executives keenly understand, compensat=
ion experts say.

I mean, fine? This measure is=C2=A0broader=C2=A0than just counting this yea=
r=E2=80=99s pay package, but still sort of arbitrary. Gains in unvested sto=
ck awards count as compensation; gains in your=C2=A0stock holdings=C2=A0do =
not:
Sixteen CEOs in the Journal analysis received compensation valued at less t=
han $5 million, about the same as in 2021. This includes CEOs, such as Mr. =
Musk and Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=99s Warren Buffett, with stakes in their =
companies that make them among the world=E2=80=99s richest people.=C2=A0
How much did Elon Musk make running Tesla last year? He began the year with=
 more than $300 billion of Tesla stock, and=C2=A0the stock was down 88% for=
 the year, though he sold a bunch along the way. Overall his net worth fell=
 by more than $100 billion, not all of it from Tesla=E2=80=99s decline (he =
did some other stuff!) but most if it. The changes in value of his=C2=A0unv=
ested Tesla compensation package=C2=A0just could not have been all that big=
 a motivating force compared to everything else. But it=E2=80=99s what gets=
 measured.

 =20
   =20
      AI M&A
   =20
 =20

Some of the mergers-and-acquisitions advisory business involves rigorous fi=
nancial analysis, hard-nosed negotiation, deep knowledge of financing marke=
ts and regulatory regimes, nuanced understanding of executive personalities=
 and corporate cultures, accumulated wisdom and personal charisma. But some=
 of it involves, like, you get a list of companies, you make 100 educated g=
uesses about companies that might want to sell, you make five educated gues=
ses about who might want to buy each of them, you write 600 polite and anal=
ytical coldish emails saying =E2=80=9Chey let=E2=80=99s talk about selling =
you to X=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s talk about you buying Y=E2=80=
=9D or whatever, and you see what you get. And=C2=A0that=C2=A0part of the j=
ob, a computer can do just so much faster than you can.  This guy knows:

Shunsaku Sagami saw firsthand the growing succession problem among entrepre=
neurs in Japan, which is grappling with the world=E2=80=99s oldest populati=
on.
The 32-year-old=E2=80=99s solution: using a proprietary database and artifi=
cial intelligence to broker deals for small- and medium-sized companies =E2=
=80=94 largely those founded by clients now on the brink of retirement. =E2=
=80=A6
Unlike M&A consultants, who often rely on regional banks for introductions =
and compete with each other for deals, M&A Research Institute uses the exte=
nsive database it built to do the matchmaking, focusing on companies with s=
ales up to =C2=A5500 million. Its advisers then do the negotiations, and an=
 agreement can be completed within six months =E2=80=94 shorter than the ti=
meframe for a typical acquisition, even when there are no regulatory hurdle=
s.=C2=A0

In the current enthusiasm for large language models like ChatGPT, people wo=
rry that these models sometimes introduce inaccuracies =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Challucinations=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0into their work product; they =
pattern-match based on existing text instead of actually =E2=80=9Cknowing=
=E2=80=9D anything. In some financial businesses this would be very bad: If=
 you are picking stocks or writing investment research, a few mistakes woul=
d really detract from performance. But in M&A that=E2=80=99s fine! Everyone=
=E2=80=99s hit rate for pitching deals is pretty low; if you send some comp=
any a cold email that gets its earnings wrong then you might lose that deal=
, but there are so many more to chase. =E2=80=9CPretty good, very confident=
 and efficient=E2=80=9D is the AI specialty, and it suits M&A pitching.
Why stop there=C2=A0I guess. Then does the AI build the financial model for=
 you? Draft the merger agreement? Those are kind of pattern-matching jobs t=
oo; I bet the AI would be fine.=C2=A0
Of course the very highest and best use of AI is to produce documents that,=
 for reasons of tradition or regulation,=C2=A0need to be produced but that =
no one will actually read.
  [4]
 Or speeches that are called for by the occasion but that  no one will list=
en to:

US Senator Richard Blumenthal opened a hearing on AI with a recording of hi=
s voice describing the risks of this emerging technology.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CToo often we have seen what happens when technology outpaces regul=
ation,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThe unbridled exploitation of personal da=
ta, the proliferation of disinformation and the deepening of societal inequ=
alities.=E2=80=9D
But he didn=E2=80=99t write it and he didn=E2=80=99t record it.
Drawing chuckles from the hearing room on Tuesday, the Connecticut Democrat=
 said the text was written by OpenAI=E2=80=99s ChatGPT and the audio was a =
voice application trained on his speeches on the Senate floor.

Oh no! Using AI might introduce errors into the opening remarks at a Senate=
 hearing! Imagine the consequences!

 =20
   =20
      People are worried about stock buybacks
   =20
 =20

I think the standard view in modern finance is that, if a company has some =
extra money and wants to give it back to shareholders, a stock buyback is b=
etter than a dividend:
=09Buybacks are more flexible than dividends: If you buy back stock this qu=
arter, and don=E2=80=99t buy back stock next quarter, that=E2=80=99s fine. =
But if you pay a dividend, people expect a steady quarterly dividend; if yo=
u just pay a few cents per share one quarter and then never again, that=E2=
=80=99s weird. The buyback gives you more flexibility to change policy in t=
he future.=09Buybacks are   more tax-efficient than dividends: If you pay a=
 dividend, every shareholder gets cash, and owes taxes on the entire amount=
 that they get. If you do a buyback, only shareholders who want the cash (t=
he ones who sell) pay taxes, and they pay taxes on their=C2=A0gains=C2=A0ra=
ther than the entire cash amount.=09Buybacks generally increase earnings pe=
r share =E2=80=94=C2=A0because there are fewer shares outstanding for rough=
ly the same earnings =E2=80=94=C2=A0and managers like to maximize earnings =
per share.=09Buybacks can be more tactical and price-sensitive: If your com=
pany=E2=80=99s stock price is too low, buying back some stock is a good tra=
de; if it is too high, you don=E2=80=99t do a buyback. A dividend is never =
a good=C2=A0trade, never a way to buy the dip or express managerial clevern=
ess.

There is however another view, which is that a dividend is a nice little tr=
eat for shareholders and they should get it. On this view, doing a buyback =
instead of a dividend is bad, because only people who=C2=A0sell stock=C2=A0=
get money from the buyback, whereas the long-term hold-forever shareholders=
 get nothing. Of course, in theory, they get=C2=A0higher earnings per share=
, a more concentrated ownership stake in the company, and stock that is wor=
th more because of the buyback. But this is uncertain; often a company will=
 do a buyback and the stock won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0be worth more. And the long-=
term shareholders=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t get the little treat.=C2=A0
Also in practice buybacks seem=C2=A0not=C2=A0to be all that tactical or pri=
ce-sensitive: In practice, executives tend to be most overconfident and flu=
sh with cash when the stock is high, and cash-strapped and nervous when the=
 stock is low, so they often buy stock at high prices rather than low ones.
Anyway the Financial Times has a nice roundup of =E2=80=9CRecord buyback sp=
ree attracts shareholder complaints=E2=80=9D:

=E2=80=9CWe would prefer buybacks to be less prevalent,=E2=80=9D said Euan =
Munro, chief executive of Newton Investment Management.
=E2=80=9CUsed badly, [buybacks] can be used to manipulate [earnings per sha=
re] numbers upwards to meet medium-term management incentive targets at the=
 expense of investments that might be important to a company=E2=80=99s long=
- term health,=E2=80=9D he said.
Daniel Peris, a fund manager at Pittsburgh-based Federated Hermes, called b=
uybacks an =E2=80=9Cenvironmental hazard=E2=80=9D.
=E2=80=9CThe dividend is just the dividend: grandma benefits, the long-term=
 holder [benefits]. Buybacks benefit traders, hedge funds, senior executive=
s [and] near-term share prices.=E2=80=9D
Leigh Himsworth, a UK equity fund manager at Fidelity, said: =E2=80=9CAs a =
shareholder you feel like you never actually get the reward=E2=80=9D with b=
uybacks. =E2=80=9CIf the market is nonplussed by it then, as a shareholder,=
 you are worse than square one, as the company has typically used up their =
cash.=E2=80=9D
Abrie Pretorius, a manager at Ninety One, said: =E2=80=9CBuybacks only crea=
te value for remaining shareholders and strong relative performance when sh=
ares are cheap and there are no better uses of that cash which would genera=
te higher returns. Most buybacks help optical [earnings per share] growth b=
ut destroy value.=E2=80=9D

The complaints tend to come from outside the US; in the US buybacks have ki=
nd of already won over dividends, and to a US reader these complaints =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0about =E2=80=9Cgrandma=E2=80=9D missing her dividend =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0seem a little quaint. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The approach we have seen in =
the US to generally prefer buybacks could be problematic if it takes root i=
n the UK,=E2=80=99=C2=A0said Michael Stiasny, M&G=E2=80=99s head of UK equi=
ties.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      Liability management
   =20
 =20

We have   talked a   lot about my   theory of modern distressed debt invest=
ing:
=09A company has $100 of debt.=09It runs into trouble and can=E2=80=99t pay=
 back the $100 of debt on schedule.=09The holders of $51 of the debt get to=
gether and say: =E2=80=9CHey, we will let you extend this debt and get some=
 breathing room. But there=E2=80=99s a price: You have to give us new debt =
worth $70 in exchange for our existing $51 of debt. But the good news is th=
at we will vote to amend the debt documents so that you can give the=C2=A0o=
ther=C2=A0guys new debt worth $10 for their $49 of debt. Net, you come out =
ahead (you cut the value of your debt from $100 to $80), we come out ahead =
(we raise our claim from $51 in a heavily levered company to $70 in a sligh=
tly safer company), and the other guys come out massively behind.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0=09The company takes the deal, it gets some breathing room, the major=
ity creditors get a nice bonus, the minority creditors get mad and sue, and=
 we move on to the next deal.

This mostly works in a world of low interest rates, though. With high inter=
est rates, the math doesn=E2=80=99t work: If the $100 of debt has fallen to=
 $40 of value due to rising rates and worsening credit, there is no way to =
give the favored creditors new debt worth $70 or even $51 without paying a =
lot more interest and burning more cash. This was a sort of boom-time form =
of distressed investing, when investors could get a lot of value for themse=
lves by taking it from other investors. When the pie is shrinking, it=E2=80=
=99s harder to get a bigger piece.
We   talked a year ago about Envision Healthcare, which did a pretty classi=
c version of this trade. It filed for bankruptcy this weekend, along with s=
ix other big companies, =E2=80=9Ca sudden burst that=E2=80=99s without prec=
edent in the 15 years that Bloomberg has been tracking the data,=E2=80=9D B=
loomberg=E2=80=99s   Amelia Pollard and Jeremy Hill report:

To some market observers, this is a clear sign =E2=80=94 and a moment that =
might be remembered for years to come =E2=80=94 that the long-awaited cull =
of companies drowning under onerous debt loads has begun in earnest. Dubbed=
 zombie companies by Wall Street, they had staggered along year after year =
even though their finances were fatally flawed. Their survival was only mad=
e possible by the uber-low interest rates that marked most of this century,=
 and so when rates began to soar last year, their fate was sealed. =E2=80=
=A6
=E2=80=9COne could characterize many of them as companies that have long ne=
eded to address their capital structures,=E2=80=9D Damian Schaible, co-head=
 of restructuring at law firm Davis Polk, said referring to the firms that =
filed in the last couple of days. =E2=80=9CAnd there=E2=80=99s a bunch more=
 on the horizon.=E2=80=9D ...
=E2=80=9CMany of these are companies where it finally made sense to just ri=
p the band-aid off and de-lever,=E2=80=9D said Schaible. =E2=80=9CWe haven=
=E2=80=99t seen that in a while because of loose documents and willingness =
by creditors to play ball with liability management transactions.=E2=80=9D

The new way to do resolve distressed-debt investor fights is also the old w=
ay: bankruptcy.=C2=A0

 =20
   =20
      The Twitter sitter stays
   =20
 =20

In 2018, Elon Musk announced on Twitter that he was considering taking Tesl=
a Inc. private and that he had =E2=80=9Cfunding secured.=E2=80=9D He did no=
t have funding secured. In the grand scheme of Elon Musk=E2=80=99s life, th=
is probably seemed like a fairly minor exaggeration, but the US Securities =
and Exchange Commission was not amused and   sued him for securities fraud.=
 Eventually he settled, paying what probably seemed to him to be a fairly s=
mall fine, and agreeing that, before he tweeted anything that might be mate=
rial to Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price, he would have a lawyer review the twee=
t. Musk then more or less immediately   went on television to say that he w=
ould not be having a lawyer review his tweets, he started tweeting unreview=
ed and not-quite-true things about Tesla=E2=80=99s numbers, the SEC   went =
back to court, and Musk sued to get out of the settlement because=C2=A0he=
=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=99t serious about it and he didn=E2=80=99t think it was fa=
ir that the SEC was.
He lost that lawsuit, he appealed, and this week he lost his appeal. =E2=80=
=9CHad Musk wished to preserve his right to tweet without even limited inte=
rnal oversight concerning certain Tesla-related topics, he had =E2=80=98the=
 right to litigate and defend against the [SEC=E2=80=99s] charges=E2=80=99 =
or to negotiate a different agreement=E2=80=94but he chose not to do so,=E2=
=80=9D  wrote the appeals court. =E2=80=9CHaving made that choice, he may n=
ot =E2=80=A6 reopen a final judgment merely because he has now changed his =
mind.=E2=80=9D
The world has moved on and I mention this mainly as a curiosity. The settle=
ment is still technically in force, but:
=09It=E2=80=99s not like Musk was obeying it anyway;=09He=C2=A0has=C2=A0sor=
t of stopped tweeting material things about Tesla, in part because since 20=
18 he bought Twitter and, like most people on Twitter these days, seems to =
prefer to tweet about Twitter; and=09All of this seems to have accomplished=
 Musk=E2=80=99s main goal, which was to make life difficult enough for the =
SEC that they wouldn=E2=80=99t bother trying to enforce securities laws aga=
inst him again because everything with him is a huge hassle. =E2=80=9CWe se=
e no evidence to support Musk=E2=80=99s contention that the SEC has used th=
e consent decree to conduct bad-faith, harassing investigations of his prot=
ected speech,=E2=80=9D writes the appeals court. =E2=80=9CTo the contrary, =
the record indicates that the SEC has opened just three inquiries into Musk=
=E2=80=99s tweets since 2018.=E2=80=9D

If   I were Musk=E2=80=99s lawyer, I wouldn=E2=80=99t tell him =E2=80=9Csur=
e you can tweet whatever you want with no consequences,=E2=80=9D because th=
at is not legally true, and in this hypothetical situation I would be givin=
g legal advice. But if I were=C2=A0Musk, that might be the lesson I would t=
ake away from all of this.

 =20
   =20
      Does Taylor Swift do closed-end fund activism?
   =20
 =20

Gosh I hope so. =E2=80=9CThe pop superstar puts her money in a niche type o=
f mutual fund, an elite investor has revealed,=E2=80=9D reports Insider, ci=
ting=C2=A0a tweet in which Boaz Weinstein claimed =E2=80=9CDid you know tha=
t=C2=A0@taylorswift13=C2=A0invests in discounted closed end funds? You thin=
k I=E2=80=99m kidding, but her father Scott told me so!=E2=80=9D Is he kidd=
ing? I dunno. Weinstein is a noted activist at discounted closed-end funds,=
 his kids are Taylor Swift fans, there are synergies. I  tell=C2=A0my=C2=A0=
kids that Cookie Monster writes a financial newsletter. Anyway Swift seems =
to be   financially savvy and  not averse to a fight; if she is big on disc=
ounted closed-end funds I hope that she is making plans to launch proxy fig=
hts, replace management, crack open the funds and sell the assets to close =
the discount. Would=C2=A0you=C2=A0want to defend against a Taylor Swift pro=
xy fight?

