<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">CEO pay</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are the chief executive officer of a pu=
blic company, you will probably get most of your pay in stock. If you do th=
e job for a while, you will end up owning a fair amount of stock. Conceptua=
lly, your financial incentives will come in roughly four forms:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You own a bunch of stock. If you do a=
 good job, the stock will go up, and you will get richer.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have gotten some stock-based awards, like, las=
t year, or two years ago, that haven=E2=80=99t fully vested yet. If you do =
a good job, the stock will go up, and these awards will be worth more. If y=
ou do a terrible job maybe you=E2=80=99ll get fired and the awards won=E2=
=80=99t vest and they=E2=80=99ll be worth zero.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">You will get paid something (cash, stock, whatever)=C2=A0<em>=
this=C2=A0</em>year. If you do a good job, the board will pay you more; if =
you do a bad job they=E2=80=99ll pay you less or fire you.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You will get paid something=C2=A0<em>next=C2=A0</e=
m>year, and the year=C2=A0<em>after</em>; the better job you do now, the mo=
re likely you are to keep your job and be well paid in the future.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All of these things can be economically meanin=
gful. For the very richest CEOs, No. 1 tends to dominate; Mark Zuckerberg a=
nd Warren Buffett get vastly richer from a 0.1% increase in their stock pri=
ces than from their annual pay packages. (Elon Musk is <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDMtMjMvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXBheS1wYWNrY=
WdlLXNob3dzLXRlc2xhLXMtbG92ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTE2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVk=
aXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MTYmdXRtX2NhbXB=
haWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB524037d7" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a mild outl=
ier</a> here.) But traditionally only No. 3 is =E2=80=9Cexecutive pay.=E2=
=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000=
000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bot=
tom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color:=
 transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That changed last year, though, when the US Se=
curities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJl=
bGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xNDk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e22784b" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">adopted new =
rules</a> requiring companies to report executive =E2=80=9Ccompensation act=
ually paid=E2=80=9D which means, for our purposes, roughly Nos. 2 and 3: =
=E2=80=9CCompensation actually paid=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxl=
cy9maW5hbC8yMDIyLzM0LTk1NjA3LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4783f938" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">includes changes</a> =E2=80=9Cin fair value (whether positive or negativ=
e) of any awards granted during the covered fiscal year =E2=80=A6=C2=A0[or]=
 in any prior fiscal year that are outstanding and unvested as of the end o=
f the covered fiscal year.=E2=80=9D So if you get a grant of a million shar=
es in 2021, they vest in 2024, and the stock loses $10 per share in 2022, t=
hen your =E2=80=9Ccompensation actually paid=E2=80=9D in 2022 includes nega=
tive $10 million of stock awards.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway we are now in the first reporting cycle=
 with these rules and the Wall Street Journal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnR=
pY2xlcy9jZW8tcGF5LXBhY2thZ2VzLWZlbGwtc2hhcnBseS1pbi0yMDIyLWFzLXRoZS1zdG9jay=
1tYXJrZXQtc2Fuay0zZDA2ZWI2OT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB3c7974ac" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">rounds up some results</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The stock awards that Elon Musk got for runnin=
g Tesla lost nearly $10 billion in value last year. Stock declines erased $=
237 million in compensation for Expedia=E2=80=99s boss and roughly $149 mil=
lion for Amazon.com Chief Executive Andy Jassy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the flip side, a pay package initially valu=
ed at about $7 million for Regeneron Pharmaceuticals chief Leonard Schleife=
r was worth nearly $100 million at the end of the year. Compensation for T-=
Mobile CEO Michael Sievert, originally about $29 million, almost tripled. O=
ccidental Petroleum boss Vicki Hollub=E2=80=99s pay quadrupled, from $15 mi=
llion to about $60 million. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The numbers show that in 2022 about two-thirds=
 of the top executives at S&amp;P 500 companies ended the year with smaller=
 pay packages than they were awarded, at least on paper. Some 140 CEOs earn=
ed more money than expected, and at 46 companies the CEOs ended with at lea=
st double what boards planned to pay them for the year, according to a Wall=
 Street Journal analysis of data from MyLogIQ.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The latest disclosures, which show the new mea=
sure of pay for the three most recent years, highlight how much CEO pay can=
 fluctuate with market tides and other factors=E2=80=94something executives=
 keenly understand, compensation experts say.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, fine? This measure is=C2=A0<em>broader=
=C2=A0</em>than just counting this year=E2=80=99s pay package, but still so=
rt of arbitrary. Gains in unvested stock awards count as compensation; gain=
s in your=C2=A0<em>stock holdings=C2=A0</em>do not:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sixteen CEOs in the Journal analys=
is received compensation valued at less than $5 million, about the same as =
in 2021. This includes CEOs, such as Mr. Musk and Berkshire Hathaway=E2=80=
=99s Warren Buffett, with stakes in their companies that make them among th=
e world=E2=80=99s richest people.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much did Elon Musk make running Tesla last=
 year? He began the year with more than $300 billion of Tesla stock, and=C2=
=A0the stock was down 88% for the year, though he sold a bunch along the wa=
y. Overall his net worth <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVz=
