<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think the standard view in modern finance is=
 that, if a company has some extra money and wants to give it back to share=
holders, a stock buyback is better than a dividend:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buybacks are more flexible than divid=
ends: If you buy back stock this quarter, and don=E2=80=99t buy back stock =
next quarter, that=E2=80=99s fine. But if you pay a dividend, people expect=
 a steady quarterly dividend; if you just pay a few cents per share one qua=
rter and then never again, that=E2=80=99s weird. The buyback gives you more=
 flexibility to change policy in the future.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">Buybacks are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDgvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLWdvdC1pdHMtZGVhbC1kb25lP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDA1MTYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBdb217c92" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  more tax-efficient</a> than dividends: If you pay=
 a dividend, every shareholder gets cash, and owes taxes on the entire amou=
nt that they get. If you do a buyback, only shareholders who want the cash =
(the ones who sell) pay taxes, and they pay taxes on their=C2=A0<em>gains=
=C2=A0</em>rather than the entire cash amount.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Buybacks generally increase earnings per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
because there are fewer shares outstanding for roughly the same earnings =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and managers <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/31501912.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY=
2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQ0MDg1ODE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC9712ff11" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
like to maximize earnings per share</a>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Buybacks can be more tactical and price-sensitive: If your company=
=E2=80=99s stock price is too low, buying back some stock is a good trade; =
if it is too high, you don=E2=80=99t do a buyback. A dividend is never a go=
od=C2=A0<em>trade</em>, never a way to buy the dip or express managerial cl=
everness.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is however another view, which is that a=
 dividend is a nice little treat for shareholders and they should get it. O=
n this view, doing a buyback instead of a dividend is bad, because only peo=
ple who=C2=A0<em>sell </em>stock=C2=A0get money from the buyback, whereas t=
he long-term hold-forever shareholders get nothing. Of course, in theory, t=
hey get=C2=A0higher earnings per share, a more concentrated ownership stake=
 in the company, and stock that is worth more because of the buyback. But t=
his is uncertain; often a company will do a buyback and the stock <em>won=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>be worth more. And the long-term shareholders=C2=A0don=
=E2=80=99t get the little treat.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also in practice buybacks seem=C2=A0<em>not=C2=
=A0</em>to be all that tactical or price-sensitive: In practice, executives=
 tend to be most overconfident and flush with cash when the stock is high, =
and cash-strapped and nervous when the stock is low, so they often buy stoc=
k at high prices rather than low ones.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the Financial Times has a nice roundup =
of =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/315019=
12.257434/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZWFhMWEzMWMtNTgwYy00MDViLWI0M=
zgtYTU5NTA0MTk4YWM4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbf777322" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Record buyba=
ck spree attracts shareholder complaints</a>=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe would prefer buybacks to be less p=
revalent,=E2=80=9D said Euan Munro, chief executive of Newton Investment Ma=
nagement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUsed badly, [buybacks] can be used to=
 manipulate [earnings per share] numbers upwards to meet medium-term manage=
ment incentive targets at the expense of investments that might be importan=
t to a company=E2=80=99s long- term health,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Daniel Peris, a fund manager at Pittsburgh-bas=
ed Federated Hermes, called buybacks an =E2=80=9Cenvironmental hazard=E2=80=
=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe dividend is just the dividend: gr=
andma benefits, the long-term holder [benefits]. Buybacks benefit traders, =
hedge funds, senior executives [and] near-term share prices.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Leigh Himsworth, a UK equity fund manager at F=
idelity, said: =E2=80=9CAs a shareholder you feel like you never actually g=
et the reward=E2=80=9D with buybacks. =E2=80=9CIf the market is nonplussed =
by it then, as a shareholder, you are worse than square one, as the company=
 has typically used up their cash.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Abrie Pretorius, a manager at Ninety One, said=
: =E2=80=9CBuybacks only create value for remaining shareholders and strong=
 relative performance when shares are cheap and there are no better uses of=
 that cash which would generate higher returns. Most buybacks help optical =
[earnings per share] growth but destroy value.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaints tend to come from outside the U=
S; in the US buybacks have kind of already won over dividends, and to a US =
reader these complaints =E2=80=94=C2=A0about =E2=80=9Cgrandma=E2=80=9D miss=
ing her dividend =E2=80=94=C2=A0seem a little quaint. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The=
 approach we have seen in the US to generally prefer buybacks could be prob=
lematic if it takes root in the UK,=E2=80=99=C2=A0said Michael Stiasny, M&a=
mp;G=E2=80=99s head of UK equities.=E2=80=9D</p>
